==English==

===Etymology===
Latin [[apostolicus]], Greek [[ἀποστολικός]] (apostolicus): compare with French [[apostolique]].

===Pronunciation===
IPA: [[WEAE]] /ˌæp.əˈstɑl.ɪk/

===Adjective===
'''apostolic'''
# pertaining to an apostle, or to the apostles, their times, or their peculiar spirit
#: ''an '''apostolical''' mission''
#: ''the '''apostolic''' age''
# according to the doctrines of the apostles; delivered or taught by the apostles
#: '''''apostolic''' faith or practice''
<!-- material copied from Webster's Revised Unabridged Dictionary (1913) -->

===Related terms===
*[[apostle]]
*[[Apostolic church]] = the Christian church; &mdash; so called on account of its apostolic foundation, doctrine, and order. The churches of Rome, Alexandria, Antioch, and Jerusalem  were called apostolic churches.

